# steps/step-32/requests.http — the Step-32 session lifecycle, through the gateway (port 8080).
# VS Code REST Client keeps a cookie jar per file, so the refresh cookie flows between requests
# automatically — exactly like a browser. curl equivalents in the lesson use -c/-b jars.

### 1. Login — the body carries the short-lived access JWT; the response ALSO sets the httpOnly
###    refresh cookie (watch the Set-Cookie header: HttpOnly; SameSite=Strict; Path=/api/auth).
# @name login
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{"username": "alice", "password": "password"}

### 2. Silent refresh — no body needed: the cookie authenticates. Response = fresh access token
###    + a ROTATED cookie (compare Set-Cookie with step 1 — the value changed).
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/refresh

### 3. Use the access token (paste from step 1 or 2) against a protected endpoint.
GET http://localhost:8080/bank/api/accounts/ACC-A
Authorization: Bearer {{login.response.body.token}}

### 4. Logout — revokes the whole refresh family server-side and clears the cookie (Max-Age=0).
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/logout

### 5. Refresh after logout → 401. The session is really gone (server-side state, not just a
###    deleted cookie — that's what an opaque, stored refresh token buys over a stateless JWT).
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/refresh

### 6. The SPA itself, served by the gateway's catch-all route (view source: the built index.html).
GET http://localhost:8080/

### 7. A deep link — no /some/client/route file exists; nginx's try_files hands React Router the wheel.
GET http://localhost:8080/login
